<Layout title="Kleisli.lean — Stochastic functions compose" favicon="✏️">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/the-natural-framework-lean/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to lean navigator</a>

    <h1>Kleisli.lean</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6"><a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/natural-framework/blob/master/NaturalFramework/Kleisli.lean"><img src="/reading/github.svg" alt="gh" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>View source on GitHub</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Defines monadic kernels (functions that return computations) and proves they form a category &mdash; they compose associatively with an identity.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Kernel</h3>
    <p>A Kernel is a function from <code>a</code> to <code>M b</code> &mdash; given an input, it produces a computation that may be stochastic. When <code>M = Id</code>, this is just a plain function <code>a &rarr; b</code>. Every pipeline stage is a Kernel. This is the Kleisli arrow that <a href="https://june.kim/the-handshake"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>the formal backbone</a> uses to model morphisms in the Stoch category.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">def</span> <span class="text-green-300">Kernel</span> (M : Type &rarr; Type) (&alpha; &beta; : Type) := &alpha; &rarr; M &beta;</code></pre>

    <h3>Kernel.comp</h3>
    <p>Kleisli composition: feed the output of the first kernel into the second, chaining via <code>bind</code>. This is how pipeline stages connect &mdash; the output of Perceive flows into Cache, Cache into Filter, and so on.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">def</span> <span class="text-green-300">Kernel.comp</span> [Monad M] (f : Kernel M &alpha; &beta;) (g : Kernel M &beta; &gamma;)
    : Kernel M &alpha; &gamma; :=
  <span class="text-blue-300">fun</span> a =&gt; f a &gt;&gt;= g</code></pre>

    <h3>Kernel.id_comp / comp_id / comp_assoc</h3>
    <p>The three category laws: composing with the identity kernel does nothing (left and right), and composition is associative. All three follow from the monad laws &mdash; this is the standard result that every lawful monad induces a Kleisli category.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">Kernel.comp_assoc</span> [Monad M] [LawfulMonad M]
    (f : Kernel M &alpha; &beta;) (g : Kernel M &beta; &gamma;) (h : Kernel M &gamma; &delta;)
    : Kernel.comp (Kernel.comp f g) h =
      Kernel.comp f (Kernel.comp g h)</code></pre>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">The proof uses <code>funext</code> (two functions are equal if they agree on all inputs) and then applies <code>bind_assoc</code> from the LawfulMonad instance.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Kleisli composition: chain functions that return lists
; a -> [b], b -> [c]  =>  a -> [c]
; (like composing stochastic stages)

(define (kleisli-comp f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (apply append (map g (f x)))))

; Stage 1: perceive — one input, two encodings
(define (perceive x)
  (list (string-append x "-visual")
        (string-append x "-audio")))

; Stage 2: cache — each encoding gets indexed
(define (cache enc)
  (list (string-append enc ":idx0")
        (string-append enc ":idx1")))

; Compose: perceive >=> cache
(define pipeline (kleisli-comp perceive cache))

(display "perceive('cat'): ")
(display (perceive "cat"))
(newline)
(display "pipeline('cat'): ")
(display (pipeline "cat"))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Kleisli composition: chain functions that return lists
# a -> [b], b -> [c]  =>  a -> [c]
# (like composing stochastic stages)

def kleisli_comp(f, g):
    return lambda x: [z for y in f(x) for z in g(y)]

# Stage 1: perceive — one input, two encodings
def perceive(x):
    return [x + "-visual", x + "-audio"]

# Stage 2: cache — each encoding gets indexed
def cache(enc):
    return [enc + ":idx0", enc + ":idx1"]

# Compose: perceive >=> cache
pipeline = kleisli_comp(perceive, cache)

print(f"perceive('cat'): {perceive('cat')}")
print(f"pipeline('cat'): {pipeline('cat')}")
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Kernel.deterministic_comp</h3>
    <p>Pure functions can be embedded as kernels (wrap the output in <code>pure</code>). This embedding preserves composition: embedding <code>g . f</code> gives the same kernel as composing the embeddings of f and g separately.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">Kernel.deterministic_comp</span> [Monad M] [LawfulMonad M]
    (f : &alpha; &rarr; &beta;) (g : &beta; &rarr; &gamma;)
    : Kernel.deterministic (M := M) (g &compfn; f) =
      Kernel.comp (Kernel.deterministic f) (Kernel.deterministic g)</code></pre>

